e that has broadened the concept of charisma to such an extent that it loses its distinctiveness – and therefore its utility. More particularly, the concept’s relevance to the study of social movements has not moved beyond generalizations. The contributors to this volume renew the debate on charismatic leadership from a historical perspective and seek to illuminate the concept’s relevance to the study of social movements. The case studies here include such leaders as Mahatma Gandhi; the architect of apartheid, Daniel F. Malan; the heroine of the Spanish Civil War, Dolores Ibarruri (la pasionaria); and Mao Zedong. These charismatic leaders were not just professional politicians or administrators, but sustained a strong symbiotic relationship with their followers, one that stimulated devotion to the leader and created a real group identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCharisma (Personality trait)xPolitical aspects. 0aPersonality and politics. 0aPolitical leadershipxPsychological aspects. 0aPolitical psychology. 0aSocial movementsxPsychological aspects. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aAvilés, Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirlik, Arif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoorts, Lindie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevy, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynebeau, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimeon, Dilip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStutje, Jan Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStutje, Jan Willem, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVelde, Henk Te, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g